    tags: ["future generations", "environment", "debt", "justice", "stewardship"],
    oneLiner: "Catholic Social Teaching holds that the present generation has moral obligations to future generations, particularly regarding the environment, fiscal responsibility, and the preservation of culture.",
    body: "Intergenerational justice is the principle that the actions of the present generation must not impose unjust burdens on those who will come after. This concept has deep roots in Catholic thinking about stewardship—the conviction that the earth and its resources are entrusted to humanity not as absolute owners but as caretakers responsible to God and to future generations. Pope Francis's Laudato Si' placed intergenerational justice at the center of Catholic environmental teaching: 'What kind of world do we want to leave to those who come after us, to children who are now growing up?' The principle extends beyond environmental concerns to fiscal policy (massive public debts that burden future taxpayers), cultural transmission (the duty to hand on the patrimony of faith, knowledge, and civilization), and institutional integrity (leaving behind functional democratic institutions and just legal frameworks). Catholic teaching challenges the short-termism of democratic politics and market economics, both of which tend to discount the future in favor of immediate gains.",
    example: "A government that funds current spending through massive borrowing, passing trillions in debt to future generations who had no voice in the decision, violates intergenerational justice just as surely as one that depletes natural resources without regard for future needs.",
    whyItMatters: "Intergenerational justice expands the moral horizon beyond the present moment, reminding us that the common good includes not only those alive today but also the billions of persons who will inherit the world we leave behind.",
