    oneLiner: "Catholic Social Teaching supports land reform as a means of ensuring that agricultural land serves the common good and is accessible to those who work it.",
    body: "Catholic Social Teaching has consistently affirmed the right to private property while insisting that this right is not absolute but subordinate to the universal destination of goods. When land ownership is concentrated in the hands of a few while masses of rural workers are landless, the Church supports land reform as a matter of justice. Pope John XXIII in Mater et Magistra, Paul VI in Populorum Progressio, and the Latin American bishops at Medellin (1968) all called for equitable distribution of land, particularly in countries where latifundia (large estates) coexist with widespread rural poverty. Land reform is not confiscation but a reordering of property relations to ensure that land fulfills its social function. The Church advocates for policies that provide secure tenure to small farmers, protect indigenous land rights, prevent speculative land grabbing by multinational corporations, and support agrarian communities with access to credit, technical assistance, and fair markets. Pope Francis has continued this tradition, warning against 'new forms of colonialism' in which foreign investors acquire vast tracts of land in developing countries for export agriculture while local populations go hungry.",
