    body: "Microfinance—the provision of small loans, savings accounts, and financial services to people too poor to access conventional banking—resonates with several principles of Catholic Social Teaching. It embodies subsidiarity by empowering individuals and small communities to take initiative rather than depending on large institutions. It reflects the preferential option for the poor by directing financial resources to those traditionally excluded from the formal economy. And it promotes integral human development by enabling the poor to become agents of their own flourishing rather than passive recipients of aid. Catholic organizations, including many religious orders and diocesan programs, operate microfinance initiatives worldwide. However, Catholic Social Teaching also warns against the potential abuses of microfinance: predatory interest rates, coercive collection practices, and the assumption that market solutions alone can solve structural poverty. Microfinance is a valuable tool but not a substitute for the broader structural reforms—just wages, land reform, education, healthcare—that the Church demands.",
