    body: "The Compendium of the Social Doctrine of the Church, published by the Pontifical Council for Justice and Peace in 2004, is the single most comprehensive and authoritative summary of Catholic Social Teaching. It synthesizes over a century of papal encyclicals, conciliar documents, and magisterial statements into a systematic, thematically organized reference work. The Compendium covers the foundations of social teaching (the dignity of the person, the common good, subsidiarity, solidarity), the family, economic life, the political community, the international community, the environment, and the promotion of peace. It is organized not chronologically but topically, making it an accessible entry point for anyone seeking to understand the Church's teaching on a specific social question. Pope John Paul II called for its creation so that the richness of Catholic Social Teaching, scattered across many documents, would be available in a single, accessible volume. The Compendium is not a replacement for the original documents but a guide to their content and a tool for formation, study, and application.",
