    tags: ["Catholic Worker", "Dorothy Day", "Peter Maurin", "hospitality", "pacifism"],
    oneLiner: "The Catholic Worker movement, founded by Dorothy Day and Peter Maurin in 1933, combines radical hospitality, voluntary poverty, and pacifism as a lived expression of Catholic Social Teaching.",
    body: "The Catholic Worker movement, founded by Dorothy Day and Peter Maurin in New York City in 1933, is one of the most distinctive expressions of Catholic Social Teaching in American history. The movement operates houses of hospitality that provide food, shelter, and community to the homeless and destitute; publishes a newspaper (The Catholic Worker, still sold for one cent) that addresses social justice from a Catholic perspective; and practices voluntary poverty in solidarity with the poor. The movement is rooted in the works of mercy, personalism (the philosophy that every social problem is ultimately a personal encounter with Christ in the poor), and a commitment to pacifism that led Day to oppose every war from World War II to Vietnam. There is no central governing structure; each Catholic Worker community is autonomous, reflecting the principle of subsidiarity. Day's cause for canonization is currently open, and Pope Francis cited her as one of four exemplary Americans in his 2015 address to the U.S. Congress. The movement challenges both capitalist individualism and statist collectivism, proposing instead a radical, Gospel-based alternative rooted in community, simplicity, and direct action.",
    example: "Dorothy Day wrote: 'The Gospel takes away our right to discriminate between the deserving and the undeserving poor.' Catholic Worker houses practice this by welcoming anyone who comes to the door, without conditions or bureaucratic screening—a radical application of Christ's words in Matthew 25: 'I was hungry and you gave me food.'",
