    term: "Liberation Theology Assessment",
    category: "social-teaching",
    tags: ["liberation theology", "Latin America", "CDF", "Marxism", "preferential option"],
    oneLiner: "The Church affirmed liberation theology's concern for the poor while correcting its uncritical use of Marxist analysis and its reduction of salvation to political liberation.",
    body: "Liberation theology emerged in Latin America in the late 1960s and 1970s as a theological movement that placed the experience of the poor at the center of theological reflection and called for the Church to actively work for their liberation from unjust structures. The Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith, under Cardinal Ratzinger, issued two important instructions: Libertatis Nuntius (1984) and Libertatis Conscientia (1986). The first identified errors in certain versions of liberation theology, particularly the uncritical adoption of Marxist class analysis, the reduction of sin to social structures, the subordination of theology to political ideology, and the tendency to interpret the Kingdom of God in purely this-worldly terms. The second instruction affirmed the legitimate aspirations of liberation theology: the preferential option for the poor, the prophetic denunciation of injustice, the importance of base communities, and the insistence that faith must bear fruit in action for justice. The Church's position is nuanced: not a blanket condemnation but a critical engagement that affirms the centrality of the poor while insisting that authentic liberation includes spiritual, not merely political, freedom.",
    example: "Gustavo Gutierrez, the Peruvian priest often called the 'father of liberation theology,' was never condemned by Rome and was eventually received warmly by Pope Francis. His mature work integrates concern for the poor with a deep mystical spirituality, exemplifying the kind of liberation theology the Church has affirmed.",
